arch:property.oc:show_val: Locus 39 is the main collapse layer for the north of the trench, below Locus 38 above the ornamental pool and below Locus 1 to the west. The soil is a fine dark brown (7.5 YR 3/3) silt. Many architectural fragments are in the matrix, including a large number of ashlars, capital fragments, and many opus sectile pieces. Also, a fragment of a triglyph and a marble sculptural element are present. Pottery, stucco, bone, metal, glass, and shell are all present. This is a large, uniform locus over much of the north of the trench, outside the main architectural areas uncovered. Part of the final collapse of the Roman Bath Complex, it is phased to Stage 6. In the south of the locus, by the ornamental pool and the small cistern, in essentially closed contexts below the foundations of these walls, were found two lamp fragments that have been dated by Dr. Deirdre Barrett. . Cat. No. 06-L-4, a volute lamp type D. G. (Barrett 2006:98), decorated with a rosette with nine petals has been dated from the beginning of the first century CE through the end of the reign of Malichus II (CE 40-70). Cat. No. 06-L-5 is a locally made lamp with an ovolos impressed on the shoulder and rim is dated to the last third of the first century CE. These two lamp fragments are essential to the dating of the original construction of the bath complex. The cannot be seen dating the entire locus, however, as they should have been part of a new locus -- the soil under the foundation wall was separate but not sealed, and so was at the time considered to be part of the same collapse layer of Locus 39 and no new locus was defined. Locus 39 is still phased to Stage 6 with its collapse.
8.18 m north south -by- 8.61 m east west.
Collapse in the northwest of the trench

Phase XI: Further collapse post-CE 5th c., possibly the result of the earthquake of 512. Fill accumulates following the disuse of the canalization systems. The remains of two bodies are found in the upper level fluvial deposits. Localized burning in some areas.
